    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "006560be_b50f4d73",
        "filename": "util/ios/exception_processor.mm",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 145,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-02T20:52:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e how about:\n\u003e \n\u003e   static const mach_header_64* this_base_address \u003d [](){\n\u003e     Dl_info dl_info;\n\u003e     dl_info.dli_fbase \u003d nullptr;\n\nDon’t rely on dli_fbase not being touched if dladdr fails. This is a good rule to follow in general. Functions normally only promise that “out” parameters like this are valid when they indicate a successful return. “Out” parameters are undefined otherwise. They may have been left untouched, but they may not have. They may be completely invalid and unusable.\n\n\u003e     if (!dladdr(reinterpret_cast\u003cconst void*\u003e(\u0026ObjcExceptionPreprocessor),\n\u003e                \u0026dl_info)) {\n\u003e       LOG(ERROR) \u003c\u003c \"dladdr: \" \u003c\u003c dlerror();\n\u003e     }\n\u003e     return reinterpret_cast\u003cconst mach_header_64*\u003e(dl_info.dli_fbase);\n\u003e   }();\n\nSo you’d want\n\n  Dl_info dl_info;\n  if (!dladdr(…)) {\n    LOG(ERROR) \u003c\u003c …;\n    return nullptr;\n  }\n  return reinterpret_cast…;",
